  <header class="container">
    <span class="eyebrow">Interactive light polarization simulator</span>
    <h1>Understand the polarization of light by controlling two orthogonal sinusoids</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Change the amplitudes and phase difference of the x- and y-components of the electric field.
      Watch the polarization ellipse from the face view, and see how the same wave appears in the side and top views as it propagates along z.
    </p>
    <section class="concept-grid" aria-label="Key concepts">
      <article class="card"><div class="n">1</div><h3>Two orthogonal components</h3><p>Light polarization is determined by the relationship between Ex and Ey at the same frequency.</p></article>
      <article class="card"><div class="n">2</div><h3>Phase difference sets shape</h3><p>δ = 0 or π gives linear polarization, while δ = ±π/2 with equal amplitudes gives circular polarization.</p></article>
      <article class="card"><div class="n">3</div><h3>Amplitude ratio sets axes</h3><p>Changing Ax and Ay transforms a circle into an ellipse and rotates the resulting polarization state.</p></article>
      <article class="card"><div class="n">4</div><h3>Front, side, and top views</h3><p>The same electromagnetic wave can be understood through its xy trajectory and its xz and yz propagation views.</p></article>
    </section>
  </header>

